en-us: A service used to set and get information about assets stored on the Roblox website.

Source: Given a placeID, this function will return a table with the version info of the place. An optional arg of page number can be used to page through all revisions (a single page may hold about 50 revisions).
en-us: Given a placeID, this function will return a table with the version info of the place. An optional arg of page number can be used to page through all revisions (a single page may hold about 50 revisions).

Source: Given a creationID, this function will return the asset that created the creationID. If no other asset created the given creationID, 0 is returned.
en-us: Given a creationID, this function will return the asset that created the creationID. If no other asset created the given creationID, 0 is returned.

Source: Given a placeID, this function will return a table with the permissions of the place. Useful for determining what kind of permissions a particular user may have for a place.
en-us: Given a placeID, this function will return a table with the permissions of the place. Useful for determining what kind of permissions a particular user may have for a place.

Source: Reverts a given place id to the version number provided. Returns true if successful on reverting, false otherwise.
en-us: Reverts a given place id to the version number provided. Returns true if successful on reverting, false otherwise.

Source: Sets the permissions for a placeID to the place accessType. An optional table (inviteList) can be included that will set the accessType for only the player names provided. The table should be set up as an array of usernames (strings).
en-us: Sets the permissions for a placeID to the place accessType. An optional table (inviteList) can be included that will set the accessType for only the player names provided. The table should be set up as an array of usernames (strings).

Source: A Color3 value that changes the hue of the atmosphere, mixed with the sky color.
en-us: A Color3 value that changes the hue of the atmosphere, mixed with the sky color.

Source: A Color3 value for the the hue the atmosphere takes on away from the sun towards the horizon, mixed with the sky color (aka extinction).
en-us: A Color3 value for the the hue the atmosphere takes on away from the sun towards the horizon, mixed with the sky color (aka extinction).

Source: A value that controls the air particulates density. The proportion of airborne particles per unit of view depth between the camera and the sky.
en-us: A value that controls the air particulates density. The proportion of airborne particles per unit of view depth between the camera and the sky.

Source: A value that increases the glow of the atmosphere around light the sun.
en-us: A value that increases the glow of the atmosphere around light the sun.

Source: A value that controls the haziness of the atmosphere between the camera and the sky (aka turbidity).
en-us: A value that controls the haziness of the atmosphere between the camera and the sky (aka turbidity).

Source: A value that controls the height of fog in the atmosphere above the horizon (not volumetric...yet...).
en-us: A value that controls the height of fog in the atmosphere above the horizon (not volumetric...yet...).

Source: A value that offsets the quantity of light scattering events among particles in the atmosphere between the camera and the sky.
en-us: A value that offsets the quantity of light scattering events among particles in the atmosphere between the camera and the sky.

en-us: Primary axis. Corresponds to the LookVector, or the first column in the part-local Attachment CFrame rotation matrix

en-us: Euler angles applied in YXZ order

en-us: Secondary axis. Corresponds to the UpVector, or the second column in the part-local Attachment CFrame rotation matrix

en-us: Secondary axis in world space. Corresponds to the UpVector, or the second column in the world space Attachment CFrame rotation matrix.

en-us: Primary axis in world space. Corresponds to the LookVector, or the first column in the world space Attachment CFrame rotation matrix.

en-us: Euler angles applied in YXZ order

en-us: Radius of the in-game visual. Value in [0, inf).

en-us: Restitution of the limit, or how elastic it is. Value in [0, 1].

en-us: Enables the angular limits around the main axis of Attachment1.

en-us: Lower angular limit around the axis of Attachment1. Value in [-180, 180].

Source: Upper angular limit around the axis of Attachment1. Value in [-180, 180].
en-us: Upper angular limit around the axis of Attachment1. Value in [-180, 180].

Source: Maximum angle between the two main axes. Value in [0, 180].
en-us: Maximum angle between the two main axes. Value in [0, 180].

Source: A structural class, not creatable
en-us: A structural class, not creatable

Source: Determines whether or not physics acts upon the Part.  If true, part stays 'Anchored' in space, not moving regardless of any collision/forces acting upon it.  If false, physics works normally on the part.
en-us: Determines whether or not physics acts upon the Part.  If true, part stays 'Anchored' in space, not moving regardless of any collision/forces acting upon it.  If false, physics works normally on the part.

Source: Destroys SurfaceJoints with all parts that are touching this Instance (including internal joints in the Instance, as in a Model).
en-us: Destroys SurfaceJoints with all parts that are touching this Instance (including internal joints in the Instance, as in a Model).

Source: Contains information regarding the Part's position and a matrix that defines the Part's rotation. Can read/write. More info
en-us: Contains information regarding the Part's position and a matrix that defines the Part's rotation. Can read/write. More info

Source: Determines whether physical interactions with other Parts are respected.  If true, will collide and react with physics to other Parts.  If false, other parts will pass thru instead of colliding
en-us: Determines whether physical interactions with other Parts are respected.  If true, will collide and react with physics to other Parts.  If false, other parts will pass thru instead of colliding

Source: Determines whether this Part casts a shadow.
en-us: Determines whether this Part casts a shadow.

Source: Color3 of the part.
en-us: Color3 of the part.

Source: A float value ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f. Sets how much the Part will rebound against another. a value of 1 is like a superball, and 0 is like a lead block.
en-us: A float value ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f. Sets how much the Part will rebound against another. a value of 1 is like a superball, and 0 is like a lead block.

Source: A float value ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f. Sets how much the Part will be able to slide. a value of 1 is no sliding, and 0 is no friction, so infinite sliding.
en-us: A float value ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f. Sets how much the Part will be able to slide. a value of 1 is no sliding, and 0 is no friction, so infinite sliding.

Source: Returns a number that is the mass of this Instance.  Mass of a Part is immutable, and is changed only by the size of the Part.
en-us: Returns a number that is the mass of this Instance.  Mass of a Part is immutable, and is changed only by the size of the Part.

en-us: Use GetMass() instead

Source: Use MakeJoints() instead
en-us: Use MakeJoints() instead

en-us: Deprecated. Use Touched instead

en-us: Determines whether building tools (in-game and studio) can manipulate this Part.  If true, no editing allowed.  If false, editing is allowed.

en-us: Creates the appropriate SurfaceJoints with all parts that are touching this Instance (including internal joints in the Instance, as in a Model). This uses the SurfaceTypes defined on the surfaces of parts to create the appropriate welds. More info

Source: If true the part will be massless when welded to another part that is not massless. The part will still have mass like a normal part if it is an assembly root part according to GetRootPart().
en-us: If true the part will be massless when welded to another part that is not massless. The part will still have mass like a normal part if it is an assembly root part according to GetRootPart().

en-us: Specifies the look and feel the Part should have. Note: this does not define the color the Part is, see BrickColor for that. More info

en-us: Rotation around X, Y, and Z axis.  Rotations applied in YXZ order.

Source: Orientation relative to parent part, or global space if there is no parent.
en-us: Orientation relative to parent part, or global space if there is no parent.

en-us: Position relative to parent part, or global space if there is no parent.

en-us: Specifies how shiny the Part is. A value of 1 is completely reflective (chrome), while a value of 0 is no reflectance (concrete wall)

en-us: Resizes a Part in the direction of the face defined by 'NormalId', by the amount specified by 'deltaAmount'. If the operation will expand the part to intersect another Instance, the part will not resize at all.  Return true if the call is successful, false otherwise.

en-us: Sets the value for the smallest change in size allowable by the Resize(NormalId, int) function.

en-us: Sets the value for the faces allowed to be resized by the Resize(NormalId, int) function.

Source: An integer from -127 to 127. Compares before other all other part properties besides massless for deciding which part is the assembly root part according to GetRootPart().
en-us: An integer from -127 to 127. Compares before other all other part properties besides massless for deciding which part is the assembly root part according to GetRootPart().

en-us: Deprecated. Use TouchEnded instead

en-us: Fired when the part stops touching another part

en-us: Sets how visible an object is. A value of 1 makes the object invisible, while a value of 0 makes the object opaque.

en-us: How fast the Part is traveling in studs/second. This property is NOT recommended to be modified directly, unless there is good reason.  Otherwise, try using a BodyForce to move a Part.

en-us: A GUI that adorns an object in the 3D world.  Add Frames/Labels/Buttons to this object to have them rendered while attached to a 3D object

en-us: If true, billboard gui will render, otherwise rendering will be skipped.

en-us: A Vector3 (x,y,z) defined in studs that will offset the gui from the extents of the 3d object it is rendering from.

en-us: Returns the camera's current roll. Roll is defined in radians, and is stored as the delta from the camera's y axis default normal vector.

en-us: The negative z-offset of the view frustum's near clipping plane.

en-us: Takes a 2D screen position and produces a Ray object to be used for 3D raycasting. Input is x,y screen coordinates, and a (optional, defaults to 0) z position which sets how far in the camera look vector to start the ray origin.

en-us: Same as ScreenPointToRay, except no GUI offsets are taken into account. Useful for things like casting a ray from the middle of the Camera.ViewportSize

en-us: Holds the x,y screen resolution of the viewport the camera is presenting (note: this can differ from the AbsoluteSize property of a full screen gui).

Returns two values, first is a Vector3 that has x,y position and z position which is distance from camera (negative if behind camera, positive if in front). Second return value is a boolean indicating if the first argument is an on-screen coordinate.
en-us: Takes a 3D position in the world and projects it onto x,y coordinates of screen space. Returns two values, first is a Vector3 that has x,y position and z position which is distance from camera (negative if behind camera, positive if in front). Second return value is a boolean indicating if the first argument is an on-screen coordinate.

en-us: If 'functionToBind' from ContextActionService:BindAction() returns Enum.ContextActionResult.Pass, the input event is considered to have not been handled by 'functionToBind' and will continue being passed to actions bound to the same input type.

Source: If 'functionToBind' from ContextActionService:BindAction() returns Enum.ContextActionResult.Sink, the input event will stop at that function and no other bound actions under it will be invoked. This is the default behavior if 'functionToBind' does not return anything or yields in any way.

en-us: A service used to bind input to various lua functions.

Source: Binds 'functionToBind' to fire when any 'inputTypes' happen. InputTypes can be variable in number and type. Types can be Enum.KeyCode, single character strings corresponding to keys, or Enum.UserInputType. 'actionName' is a key used by many other ContextActionService functions to query state. 'createTouchButton' if true will create a button on screen on touch devices.  This button will fire 'functionToBind' with three arguments: first argument is the actionName, second argument is the UserInputState of the input, and the third is the InputObject that fired this function. If 'functionToBind' yields or returns nil or Enum.ContextActionResult.Sink, the input will be sunk. If it returns Enum.ContextActionResult.Pass, the next bound action in the stack will be invoked.
en-us: Binds 'functionToBind' to fire when any 'inputTypes' happen. InputTypes can be variable in number and type. Types can be Enum.KeyCode, single character strings corresponding to keys, or Enum.UserInputType. 'actionName' is a key used by many other ContextActionService functions to query state. 'createTouchButton' if true will create a button on screen on touch devices.  This button will fire 'functionToBind' with three arguments: first argument is the actionName, second argument is the UserInputState of the input, and the third is the InputObject that fired this function. If 'functionToBind' yields or returns nil or Enum.ContextActionResult.Sink, the input will be sunk. If it returns Enum.ContextActionResult.Pass, the next bound action in the stack will be invoked.

Source: Returns a table with all bound action info. Each entry is a key with 'actionName' and value being the same table you would get from ContextActionService:GetBoundActionInfo('actionName').
en-us: Returns a table with all bound action info. Each entry is a key with 'actionName' and value being the same table you would get from ContextActionService:GetBoundActionInfo('actionName').

Source: Returns a table with info regarding the function bound with 'actionName'. Table has the keys 'title' (current title that was set with SetTitle) 'image' (image set with SetImage) 'description' (description set with SetDescription) 'inputTypes' (tuple containing all input bound for this 'actionName') 'createTouchButton' (whether or not we created a touch button for this 'actionName').
en-us: Returns a table with info regarding the function bound with 'actionName'. Table has the keys 'title' (current title that was set with SetTitle) 'image' (image set with SetImage) 'description' (description set with SetDescription) 'inputTypes' (tuple containing all input bound for this 'actionName') 'createTouchButton' (whether or not we created a touch button for this 'actionName').

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then this will return the touch button (if was created). Returns nil if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether button will be retrievable when button is manipulated.
en-us: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then this will return the touch button (if was created). Returns nil if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether button will be retrievable when button is manipulated.

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'description' is set as the description of the bound action. This description will appear for users in a listing of current actions availables.

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'image' is set as the image of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether image will be set when button is manipulated.
en-us: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'image' is set as the image of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether image will be set when button is manipulated.

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'position' is set as the position of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether position will be set when button is manipulated.
en-us: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'position' is set as the position of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether position will be set when button is manipulated.

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'title' is set as the title of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether title will be set when button is manipulated.
en-us: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, then 'title' is set as the title of the touch button. Does nothing if a touch button was not created. No guarantees are made whether title will be set when button is manipulated.

Source: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, removes function from being called by all input that it was bound by (if function was also bound by a different action name as well, those bound input are still active). Will also remove any touch button created (if button was manipulated manually there is no guarantee it will be cleaned up).
en-us: If 'actionName' key contains a bound action, removes function from being called by all input that it was bound by (if function was also bound by a different action name as well, those bound input are still active). Will also remove any touch button created (if button was manipulated manually there is no guarantee it will be cleaned up).

Source: A UDim2 value describing the size of the GuiObject on screen in both absolute and relative coordinates. More information on UDim2 is available here.
en-us: A UDim2 value describing the size of the GuiObject on screen in both absolute and relative coordinates. More information on UDim2 is available here.

Source: The direction(s) that an object can be resized in. More info.
en-us: The direction(s) that an object can be resized in. More info.

Source: Fired when a user holds at least one finger for a short amount of time on the same screen position on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user holds at least one finger for a short amount of time on the same screen position on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user drags at least one finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'totalTranslation' is a Vector2, indicating how far the pan gesture has gone from its starting point. 'velocity' is a Vector2 that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed in each dimension. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.
en-us: Fired when a user drags at least one finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'totalTranslation' is a Vector2, indicating how far the pan gesture has gone from its starting point. 'velocity' is a Vector2 that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed in each dimension. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.

Source: Fired when a user pinches their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the pinch gesture. 'scale' is a float that indicates the difference from the beginning of the pinch gesture. 'velocity' is a float indicating how quickly the pinch gesture is happening. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user pinches their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the pinch gesture. 'scale' is a float that indicates the difference from the beginning of the pinch gesture. 'velocity' is a float indicating how quickly the pinch gesture is happening. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user rotates two fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'rotation' is a float indicating how much the rotation has gone from the start of the gesture. 'velocity' is a float that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user rotates two fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'rotation' is a float indicating how much the rotation has gone from the start of the gesture. 'velocity' is a float that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user swipes their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'swipeDirection' is an Enum.SwipeDirection, indicating the direction the user swiped. 'numberOfTouches' is an int that indicates how many touches were involved with the gesture.  This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user swipes their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'swipeDirection' is an Enum.SwipeDirection, indicating the direction the user swiped. 'numberOfTouches' is an int that indicates how many touches were involved with the gesture.  This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user taps their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the tap gesture. This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user taps their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the tap gesture. This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Smoothly moves a GuiObject from its current position to 'endPosition'. The only required argument is 'endPosition'. More info
en-us: Smoothly moves a GuiObject from its current position to 'endPosition'. The only required argument is 'endPosition'. More info

Source: Smoothly translates a GuiObject's current size to 'endSize'. The only required argument is 'endSize'. More info
en-us: Smoothly translates a GuiObject's current size to 'endSize'. The only required argument is 'endSize'. More info

Source: Smoothly translates a GuiObject's current size to 'endSize', and also smoothly translates the GuiObject's current position to 'endPosition'. The only required arguments are 'endSize' and 'endPosition'. More info
en-us: Smoothly translates a GuiObject's current size to 'endSize', and also smoothly translates the GuiObject's current position to 'endPosition'. The only required arguments are 'endSize' and 'endPosition'. More info

Source: Describes the ordering in which overlapping GuiObjects will be drawn. A value of 1 is drawn first, while higher values are drawn in ascending order (each value draws over the last).
en-us: Describes the ordering in which overlapping GuiObjects will be drawn. A value of 1 is drawn first, while higher values are drawn in ascending order (each value draws over the last).

Source: The GuiService is a special service, which currently allows developers to control what GuiObject is currently being selected by the Gamepad Gui navigator, and allows clients to check if Roblox's main menu is currently open. This service has a lot of hidden members, which are mainly used internally by Roblox's CoreScripts.
en-us: The GuiService is a special service, which currently allows developers to control what GuiObject is currently being selected by the Gamepad Gui navigator, and allows clients to check if Roblox's main menu is currently open. This service has a lot of hidden members, which are mainly used internally by Roblox's CoreScripts.

Source:
Callback that is executed for pending Developer Product receipts.

If this function does not return Enum.ProductPurchaseDecision.PurchaseGranted, then you will not be granted the money for the purchase!

The callback will be invoked with a table, containing the following informational fields:

  • PlayerId: int64 - the id of the player making the purchase.
  • PlaceIdWherePurchased: int64: - the specific place where the purchase was made.
  • PurchaseId: string - a unique identifier for the purchase, should be used to prevent granting an item multiple times for one purchase.
  • ProductId: int64 - the id of the purchased product.
  • CurrencyType: CurrencyType - the type of currency used (Tix, Robux).
  • CurrencySpent: int - the amount of currency spent on the product for this purchase.
en-us:
Callback that is executed for pending Developer Product receipts.

If this function does not return Enum.ProductPurchaseDecision.PurchaseGranted, then you will not be granted the money for the purchase!

The callback will be invoked with a table, containing the following informational fields:

  • PlayerId: int64 - the id of the player making the purchase.
  • PlaceIdWherePurchased: int64: - the specific place where the purchase was made.
  • PurchaseId: string - a unique identifier for the purchase, should be used to prevent granting an item multiple times for one purchase.
  • ProductId: int64 - the id of the purchased product.
  • CurrencyType: CurrencyType - the type of currency used (Tix, Robux).
  • CurrencySpent: int - the amount of currency spent on the product for this purchase.

Source: Will prompt 'player' to purchase the item associated with 'assetId'.  'equipIfPurchased' is an optional argument that will give the item to the player immediately if they buy it (only applies to gear).  'currencyType' is also optional and will attempt to prompt the user with a specified currency if the product can be purchased with this currency, otherwise we use the default currency of the product.
en-us: Will prompt 'player' to purchase the item associated with 'assetId'.  'equipIfPurchased' is an optional argument that will give the item to the player immediately if they buy it (only applies to gear).  'currencyType' is also optional and will attempt to prompt the user with a specified currency if the product can be purchased with this currency, otherwise we use the default currency of the product.

en-us: Target speed in studs per second. This value is unsigned as the servo will always move toward its target. Value in [0, inf).

Source: Target position of Attachment1 with respect to Attachment0 along the slider axis. Value in (-inf, inf).

en-us: The ambient sound environment.  May not work when using hardware sound

Source: the relative distance factor, compared to 1.0 meters.
en-us: the relative distance factor, compared to 1.0 meters.

Source: The doppler scale is a general scaling factor for how much the pitch varies due to doppler shifting in 3D sound. Doppler is the pitch bending effect when a sound comes towards the listener or moves away from it, much like the effect you hear when a train goes past you with its horn sounding. With dopplerscale you can exaggerate or diminish the effect.
en-us: The doppler scale is a general scaling factor for how much the pitch varies due to doppler shifting in 3D sound. Doppler is the pitch bending effect when a sound comes towards the listener or moves away from it, much like the effect you hear when a train goes past you with its horn sounding. With dopplerscale you can exaggerate or diminish the effect.

Source: Setting this value makes the sound drop off faster or slower. The higher the value, the faster volume will attenuate, and conversely the lower the value, the slower it will attenuate. For example a rolloff factor of 1 will simulate the real world, where as a value of 2 will make sounds attenuate 2 times quicker.
en-us: Setting this value makes the sound drop off faster or slower. The higher the value, the faster volume will attenuate, and conversely the lower the value, the slower it will attenuate. For example a rolloff factor of 1 will simulate the real world, where as a value of 2 will make sounds attenuate 2 times quicker.

en-us: Makes the parent part or model object fantastic

en-us: Makes the parent part emit light in a conical shape

en-us: The number of coils in the in-game visual. Value in [0, 8].

Source: Current distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: Current distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).

Source: The damping parameter of the spring. The force is scaled with respect to relative velocity. The units of this property are force / velocity. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The damping parameter of the spring. The force is scaled with respect to relative velocity. The units of this property are force / velocity. Value in [0, inf).

Source: The distance (in studs) between the two attachments at which the spring exerts no stiffness force. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The distance (in studs) between the two attachments at which the spring exerts no stiffness force. Value in [0, inf).

Source: Enables limits on the length of the spring.
en-us: Enables limits on the length of the spring.

Source: The maximum force that the spring can apply. Useful to prevent instabilities. The units are mass * studs / seconds^2. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The maximum force that the spring can apply. Useful to prevent instabilities. The units are mass * studs / seconds^2. Value in [0, inf).

Source: Maximum spring length, or the maxium distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: Maximum spring length, or the maxium distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).

Source: Minimum spring length, or the minimum distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: Minimum spring length, or the minimum distance between the two attachments. Value in [0, inf).

Source: The radius of the in-game spring coil visual. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The radius of the in-game spring coil visual. Value in [0, inf).

Source: The stiffness parameter of the spring. Force is scaled based on distance from the free length. The units of this property are force / distance. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The stiffness parameter of the spring. Force is scaled based on distance from the free length. The units of this property are force / distance. Value in [0, inf).

Source: The thickness of the spring wire (diameter) in the in-game visual. Value in [0, inf).
en-us: The thickness of the spring wire (diameter) in the in-game visual. Value in [0, inf).

Source: A container instance that contains Scripts.  Useful only for Plugins.  When Studio starts, we load plugins into the 'UserPlugin' data model and execute Scripts contained in StandalonePluginScripts container. If a plugin doesn't have such a container then the plugin isn't loaded into UserPlugin data model.  When a data model for a place is created (e.g. the Edit data model), we load plugins into said data model and execute only those Scripts which are not contained in StandalonePluginScripts container.
en-us: A container instance that contains Scripts.  Useful only for Plugins.  When Studio starts, we load plugins into the 'UserPlugin' data model and execute Scripts contained in StandalonePluginScripts container. If a plugin doesn't have such a container then the plugin isn't loaded into UserPlugin data model.  When a data model for a place is created (e.g. the Edit data model), we load plugins into said data model and execute only those Scripts which are not contained in StandalonePluginScripts container.

Source: An object linked to an instance that animates properties on the instance over a specified period of time. Useful for easily moving UI objects around, rotating objects, etc. without having to write a lot of code. To create a new tween, please use TweenService:Create.
en-us: An object linked to an instance that animates properties on the instance over a specified period of time. Useful for easily moving UI objects around, rotating objects, etc. without having to write a lot of code. To create a new tween, please use TweenService:Create.

Source: Stops the tween animation. Animation can be restarted by calling Play(). Animation will start from the beginning values.
en-us: Stops the tween animation. Animation can be restarted by calling Play(). Animation will start from the beginning values.

Source: Fires when the tween either reaches PlaybackState Completed or Cancelled. PlaybackState of one of these types is passed as the first arg to the function listening to this event.
en-us: Fires when the tween either reaches PlaybackState Completed or Cancelled. PlaybackState of one of these types is passed as the first arg to the function listening to this event.

Source: Temporarily stops the tween animation. Animation can be resumed by calling Play().
en-us: Temporarily stops the tween animation. Animation can be resumed by calling Play().

Source: Starts or resumes (if Tween.PlaybackState is Paused) the tween animation. If current PlaybackState is Cancelled, this property will reset the tween to the beginning properties and play the animations from the beginning.
en-us: Starts or resumes (if Tween.PlaybackState is Paused) the tween animation. If current PlaybackState is Cancelled, this property will reset the tween to the beginning properties and play the animations from the beginning.

Source: The current state of how the tween is animating. Possible values are Begin, Playing, Paused, Completed and Cancelled. This property is modified by using functions such as Tween:Play(), Tween:Pause(), and Tween:Cancel(). Read-only.
en-us: The current state of how the tween is animating. Possible values are Begin, Playing, Paused, Completed and Cancelled. This property is modified by using functions such as Tween:Play(), Tween:Pause(), and Tween:Cancel(). Read-only.

Source: The object this tween is operating on. Read-only.
en-us: The object this tween is operating on. Read-only.

Source: Service responsible for creating tweens on instances.
en-us: Service responsible for creating tweens on instances.

Source: Creates a Tween object bound to a particular Instance. The first arg is the Instance to tween. The second arg is a TweenInfo struct, which specifies how a tween should behave. The third arg is a table, which should specify the properties to tween as keys, with the end value specified as values to the keys.
en-us: Creates a Tween object bound to a particular Instance. The first arg is the Instance to tween. The second arg is a TweenInfo struct, which specifies how a tween should behave. The third arg is a table, which should specify the properties to tween as keys, with the end value specified as values to the keys.

Source: Transforms a linear alpha to a given EasingStyle and EasingDirection.
en-us: Transforms a linear alpha to a given EasingStyle and EasingDirection.

Source: Specifies how the tween animates. Read-only.
en-us: Specifies how the tween animates. Read-only.

Source: Ensures a GuiObject will always have a particular aspect ratio. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.
en-us: Ensures a GuiObject will always have a particular aspect ratio. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.

Source: The aspect ratio to maintain. This is the width/height. Only positive numbers allowed.
en-us: The aspect ratio to maintain. This is the width/height. Only positive numbers allowed.

Source: Describes how the aspect ratio will determine its size. Options are FitWithinMaxSize, ScaleWithParentSize. FitWithinMaxSize will make the element the maximum size it can be within the current possible AbsoluteSize of the element while maintaining the AspectRatio. ScaleWithParentSize will make the element the closest to the parent elements maximum size while maintaining aspect ratio.
en-us: Describes how the aspect ratio will determine its size. Options are FitWithinMaxSize, ScaleWithParentSize. FitWithinMaxSize will make the element the maximum size it can be within the current possible AbsoluteSize of the element while maintaining the AspectRatio. ScaleWithParentSize will make the element the closest to the parent elements maximum size while maintaining aspect ratio.

Source: Describes which axis to use when determining the new size of the element, while keeping respect to the aspect ratio.
en-us: Describes which axis to use when determining the new size of the element, while keeping respect to the aspect ratio.

Source: Modify corner properties of parent GuiObject.
en-us: Modify corner properties of parent GuiObject.

Source: Round corner with specified radius.
en-us: Round corner with specified radius.

Source: Apply a gradient to the parent GuiObject.
en-us: Apply a gradient to the parent GuiObject.

Source: The (sequence of) color3 of the gradient.
en-us: The (sequence of) color3 of the gradient.

Source: Offset of gradient center in scale.
en-us: Offset of gradient center in scale.

Source: Clockwise rotation in degrees.
en-us: Clockwise rotation in degrees.

Source: The (sequence of) transparency of the gradient.
en-us: The (sequence of) transparency of the gradient.

Source: Sets the position of UI elements in a 2D grid (this can be modified to 1D grid for list layout). This will also set the elements to a particular size, although this can be overridden with particular constraints on elements. You can use a UIGridLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIGridLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.
en-us: Sets the position of UI elements in a 2D grid (this can be modified to 1D grid for list layout). This will also set the elements to a particular size, although this can be overridden with particular constraints on elements. You can use a UIGridLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIGridLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.

Source: Returns the current size of the grid. If more elements are added, this can increase. If elements are removed this can decrease.
en-us: Returns the current size of the grid. If more elements are added, this can increase. If elements are removed this can decrease.

Source: How much space between elements there should be.
en-us: How much space between elements there should be.

Source: Denotes what size each element should be. Can be overridden by elements using constraints on individual elements.
en-us: Denotes what size each element should be. Can be overridden by elements using constraints on individual elements.

Source: Determines how many cells over in the FillDirection we go before starting a new row or column. Set to 0 for max cell count.  Will be clamped if this is set higher than the parent container allows room for.
en-us: Determines how many cells over in the FillDirection we go before starting a new row or column. Set to 0 for max cell count.  Will be clamped if this is set higher than the parent container allows room for.

Source: Which corner we start laying the elements out from. Can be TopLeft, TopRight, BottomLeft, BottomRight.
en-us: Which corner we start laying the elements out from. Can be TopLeft, TopRight, BottomLeft, BottomRight.

Source: Forces a relayout of all elements. Useful when sort is set to Custom.
en-us: Forces a relayout of all elements. Useful when sort is set to Custom.

Source: Determines which direction to fill the grid. Can be Horizontal or Vertical.
en-us: Determines which direction to fill the grid. Can be Horizontal or Vertical.

Source: Determines how grid is placed within it's parent's container in the x direction. Can be Left, Center, or Right.
en-us: Determines how grid is placed within it's parent's container in the x direction. Can be Left, Center, or Right.

Source: When SortOrder is set to Custom, this lua function is used to determine the ordering of elements. Function should take two arguments (each will be an Instance child to compare), and return true if a comes before b, otherwise return false. In other words, use this function the same way you would use a table.sort function. The sorting should be deterministic, otherwise sort will fail and fall back to name order.
en-us: When SortOrder is set to Custom, this lua function is used to determine the ordering of elements. Function should take two arguments (each will be an Instance child to compare), and return true if a comes before b, otherwise return false. In other words, use this function the same way you would use a table.sort function. The sorting should be deterministic, otherwise sort will fail and fall back to name order.

Source: Determines how we decide which element to place next. Can be Name or Custom. If using Custom, make sure SetCustomSortFunction was called with an appropriate sort function.
en-us: Determines how we decide which element to place next. Can be Name or Custom. If using Custom, make sure SetCustomSortFunction was called with an appropriate sort function.

Source: Determines how grid is placed within it's parent's container in the y direction. Can be Top, Center, or Bottom.
en-us: Determines how grid is placed within it's parent's container in the y direction. Can be Top, Center, or Bottom.

Source: Sets the position of UI elements in a list. You can use a UIListLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIListLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.
en-us: Sets the position of UI elements in a list. You can use a UIListLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIListLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.

Source: Determines the amount of free space between each element. Can be set either using scale (Percentage of parent's size in the current direction) or offset (a static spacing value, similar to pixel size).
en-us: Determines the amount of free space between each element. Can be set either using scale (Percentage of parent's size in the current direction) or offset (a static spacing value, similar to pixel size).

Source: The padding to apply on the bottom side relative to the parent's normal size.
en-us: The padding to apply on the bottom side relative to the parent's normal size.

Source: The padding to apply on the left side relative to the parent's normal size.
en-us: The padding to apply on the left side relative to the parent's normal size.

Source: The padding to apply on the right side relative to the parent's normal size.
en-us: The padding to apply on the right side relative to the parent's normal size.

Source: The padding to apply on the top side relative to the parent's normal size.
en-us: The padding to apply on the top side relative to the parent's normal size.

Source: Creates a paged viewing window, like the home screen of a mobile device. You can use a UIPageLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIPageLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.
en-us: Creates a paged viewing window, like the home screen of a mobile device. You can use a UIPageLayout by parenting it to a GuiObject. The UIPageLayout will then apply itself to all of its GuiObject siblings.

Source: Whether or not to animate transitions between pages.
en-us: Whether or not to animate transitions between pages.

Source: Whether or not the page layout wraps around at the ends.
en-us: Whether or not the page layout wraps around at the ends.

Source: The page that is either currently being displayed or is the target of the current animation.
en-us: The page that is either currently being displayed or is the target of the current animation.

Source: The easing direction to use when performing an animation.
en-us: The easing direction to use when performing an animation.

Source: The easing style to use when performing an animation.
en-us: The easing style to use when performing an animation.

Source: If the instance is in the layout, then it sets CurrentPage to it and animtes to it. If circular layout is set, it will take the shortest path.
en-us: If the instance is in the layout, then it sets CurrentPage to it and animtes to it. If circular layout is set, it will take the shortest path.

Source: If the index is >= 0 and less than the size of the layout, acts like JumpTo. If it's out of bounds and circular is set, it will animate the full distance between the in-bounds index of CurrentPage and the new index.
en-us: If the index is >= 0 and less than the size of the layout, acts like JumpTo. If it's out of bounds and circular is set, it will animate the full distance between the in-bounds index of CurrentPage and the new index.

Source: Sets CurrentPage to the page after the current page and animates to it, or does nothing if there isn't a next page.
en-us: Sets CurrentPage to the page after the current page and animates to it, or does nothing if there isn't a next page.

Source: Determines the amount that pages are separated from each other by. Can be set either using scale (Percentage of parent's size in the current direction) or offset (a static spacing value, similar to pixel size).
en-us: Determines the amount that pages are separated from each other by. Can be set either using scale (Percentage of parent's size in the current direction) or offset (a static spacing value, similar to pixel size).

Source: Fires when a page comes into view, and is going to be rendered.
en-us: Fires when a page comes into view, and is going to be rendered.

Source: Fires when a page leaves view, and will not be rendered.
en-us: Fires when a page leaves view, and will not be rendered.

Source: Sets CurrentPage to the page after the current page and animates to it, or does nothing if there isn't a next page.
en-us: Sets CurrentPage to the page after the current page and animates to it, or does nothing if there isn't a next page.

Source: Fires when an animation to CurrentPage is completed without being cancelled, and the view stops scrolling.
en-us: Fires when an animation to CurrentPage is completed without being cancelled, and the view stops scrolling.

Source: The length of the animation.
en-us: The length of the animation.

Source: Uniformly scales a GUI object and all its children.
en-us: Uniformly scales a GUI object and all its children.

Source: The scale factor to apply.
en-us: The scale factor to apply.

Source: Ensures a GuiObject does not become smaller or larger than the min and max size. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.
en-us: Ensures a GuiObject does not become smaller or larger than the min and max size. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.

Source: The biggest size the GuiObject is allowed to be.
en-us: The biggest size the GuiObject is allowed to be.

Source: The smallest size the GuiObject is allowed to be.
en-us: The smallest size the GuiObject is allowed to be.

Source: Provides a layout of rows and columns that are sized based on the cells in them.
en-us: Provides a layout of rows and columns that are sized based on the cells in them.

Source: Whether the table should expand to fill the available space of its container, column-wise.
en-us: Whether the table should expand to fill the available space of its container, column-wise.

Source: Whether the table should expand to fill the available space of its container, row-wise.
en-us: Whether the table should expand to fill the available space of its container, row-wise.

Source: Whether the direct siblings are considered the rows or the columns. The children of the direct siblings are the columns or rows, respectively.
en-us: Whether the direct siblings are considered the rows or the columns. The children of the direct siblings are the columns or rows, respectively.

Source: The amount of padding to insert in between the cells of the table.
en-us: The amount of padding to insert in between the cells of the table.

Source: Ensures a GuiObject with text does not allow the font size to become larger or smaller than min and max text sizes. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.
en-us: Ensures a GuiObject with text does not allow the font size to become larger or smaller than min and max text sizes. If an element with a constraint is under the control of a layout, the constraint takes precedence in determining the elements size, but not position. You can use a Constraint by parenting it to the element you wish to constrain.

Source: The biggest size the font is allowed to be.

Source: The smallest size the font is allowed to be.
en-us: The smallest size the font is allowed to be.

Source: Returns true if the local device has an accelerometer, false otherwise.
en-us: Returns true if the local device has an accelerometer, false otherwise.

Source: Fired when a user moves a device that has an accelerometer. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user moves a device that has an accelerometer. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when the force of gravity changes on a device that has an accelerometer. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when the force of gravity changes on a device that has an accelerometer. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user rotates a device that has an gyroscope. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Gyroscope, and position that shows total rotation in each local device axis.  The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. A second argument of Vector4 is the device's current quaternion rotation in reference to it's default reference frame. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user rotates a device that has an gyroscope. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Gyroscope, and position that shows total rotation in each local device axis.  The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. A second argument of Vector4 is the device's current quaternion rotation in reference to it's default reference frame. This event only fires locally.

Source: Returns an InputObject that describes the device's current acceleration. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis.  The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Returns an InputObject that describes the device's current acceleration. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis.  The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. This event only fires locally.

Source: Returns an InputObject that describes the device's current gravity vector. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Returns an InputObject that describes the device's current gravity vector. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Accelerometer, and position that shows the g force in each local device axis. The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. This event only fires locally.

Source: Returns an InputObject and a Vector4 that describes the device's current rotation vector. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Gyroscope, and position that shows total rotation in each local device axis. The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. The Vector4 is the device's current quaternion rotation in reference to it's default reference frame. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Returns an InputObject and a Vector4 that describes the device's current rotation vector. This is fired with an InputObject, which has type Enum.InputType.Gyroscope, and position that shows total rotation in each local device axis. The delta property describes the amount of rotation that last happened. The Vector4 is the device's current quaternion rotation in reference to it's default reference frame. This event only fires locally.

Source: Returns true if the local device has an gyroscope, false otherwise.
en-us: Returns true if the local device has an gyroscope, false otherwise.

Source: Fired when a user begins interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse button down, touch begin, keyboard button down, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user begins interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse button down, touch begin, keyboard button down, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user changes interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse move, touch move, mouse wheel, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user changes interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse move, touch move, mouse wheel, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user stops interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse button up, touch end, keyboard button up, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user stops interacting via a Human-Computer Interface device (Mouse button up, touch end, keyboard button up, etc.). 'inputObject' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Returns true if the local device accepts keyboard input, false otherwise.
en-us: Returns true if the local device accepts keyboard input, false otherwise.

Source: Returns true if the local device accepts mouse input, false otherwise.
en-us: Returns true if the local device accepts mouse input, false otherwise.

Source: Fired when a user stops text entry into a textbox (usually by pressing return or clicking/tapping somewhere else on the screen). Argument is the textbox that was taken out of focus. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user stops text entry into a textbox (usually by pressing return or clicking/tapping somewhere else on the screen). Argument is the textbox that was taken out of focus. This event only fires locally.

Source: Fired when a user clicks/taps on a textbox to begin text entry. Argument is the textbox that was put in focus. This also fires if a textbox forces focus on the user. This event only fires locally.
en-us: Fired when a user clicks/taps on a textbox to begin text entry. Argument is the textbox that was put in focus. This also fires if a textbox forces focus on the user. This event only fires locally.

Source: Returns true if the local device accepts touch input, false otherwise.
en-us: Returns true if the local device accepts touch input, false otherwise.

Source: Fired when a user moves their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user moves their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user holds at least one finger for a short amount of time on the same screen position on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user holds at least one finger for a short amount of time on the same screen position on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user moves their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user moves their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user drags at least one finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'totalTranslation' is a Vector2, indicating how far the pan gesture has gone from its starting point. 'velocity' is a Vector2 that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed in each dimension. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user drags at least one finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'totalTranslation' is a Vector2, indicating how far the pan gesture has gone from its starting point. 'velocity' is a Vector2 that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed in each dimension. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user pinches their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the pinch gesture. 'scale' is a float that indicates the difference from the beginning of the pinch gesture. 'velocity' is a float indicating how quickly the pinch gesture is happening. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user pinches their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the pinch gesture. 'scale' is a float that indicates the difference from the beginning of the pinch gesture. 'velocity' is a float indicating how quickly the pinch gesture is happening. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user rotates two fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'rotation' is a float indicating how much the rotation has gone from the start of the gesture. 'velocity' is a float that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user rotates two fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the gesture. 'rotation' is a float indicating how much the rotation has gone from the start of the gesture. 'velocity' is a float that indicates how quickly the gesture is being performed. 'state' indicates the Enum.UserInputState of the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user places their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user places their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touch' is an InputObject, which contains useful data for querying user input.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user swipes their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'swipeDirection' is an Enum.SwipeDirection, indicating the direction the user swiped. 'numberOfTouches' is an int that indicates how many touches were involved with the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user swipes their fingers on a TouchEnabled device. 'swipeDirection' is an Enum.SwipeDirection, indicating the direction the user swiped. 'numberOfTouches' is an int that indicates how many touches were involved with the gesture.  This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.

Source: Fired when a user taps their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the tap gesture. This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
en-us: Fired when a user taps their finger on a TouchEnabled device. 'touchPositions' is a Lua array of Vector2, each indicating the position of all the fingers involved in the tap gesture. This event only fires locally.  This event will always fire regardless of game state.
